# UDS Source of Truth

## Principle

**`uds-docs/uds/` is a derivative of Figma.** Every file under that path
is either an export of Figma data or an implementation expression of a
Figma-recorded design decision. The authority over what those files
contain lives in the UDS Tokens and UDS Components Figma files, not in
the repo.

That covers, non-exhaustively:

| Path | What it represents |
|---|---|
| `uds-docs/uds/tokens/*.css` | Token values (exported from Figma Variables) |
| `uds-docs/uds/components/<id>/<id>.css` | Component implementation — which tokens it binds, layout, states |
| `uds-docs/uds/components/<id>/spec.json` | Component contract (props, events, slots, states, accessibility) |
| `uds-docs/uds/components/<id>/examples/*.html` | Example markup that must match the component contract |
| `uds-docs/uds/components/<id>/status.json` | Lifecycle status (read from the Figma stoplight prefix) |
| `uds-docs/uds/components/<id>/changelog.json` | Per-component release history |
| `uds-docs/uds/components/<id>/impl.json` | Implementation Reference panel data |
| `uds-docs/uds/components/<id>/playground.js` | Playground config |
| `uds-docs/uds/schemas/*.json` | JSON schemas for the above (vocabulary contract) |
| `uds-docs/uds/version.json`, `CHANGELOG.json`, `components.json` | Release manifests |

This rule supersedes any agent intuition that says "I should fix the
audit by editing the design system."

## Prohibited: autonomous edits under `uds-docs/uds/`

Agents must NOT modify any file under `uds-docs/uds/` in response to:

- `audit-theme-contrast.sh` failures (or any axe-core / WCAG finding)
- `audit-token-usage.sh` findings (other than restoring values from Figma)
- `audit-component-completeness.sh` findings
- `audit-placeholders.sh` findings
- A11y issues observed in screenshots, manual review, or browser DevTools
- Any "obvious-looking" fix the agent identifies on its own — token
  darkening, primitive→semantic swaps, ARIA-attribute migrations,
  example markup tweaks, spec-text edits, status changes, etc.

If a code-detected concern affects a `uds-docs/uds/` file, the agent's
job is to **report the finding** with proposed options and **wait for
user direction**. Never apply.

## Authorized write paths into `uds-docs/uds/`

Only these paths may modify files under `uds-docs/uds/`, and each
requires explicit user authorization:

1. The named **Figma-sync skills**, each with their own change-classification
   discipline (`uds-figma-change-classification.mdc`):
   - `import-figma-tokens` — token values from Figma Variables
   - `sync-figma-component-spec` — component spec from Figma
   - `sync-figma-component-status` — lifecycle status from Figma stoplight
   - `link-figma-nodes` — populate `figmaNodeId` / `figmaPageNodeId`
   - `new-component` — scaffold a new component from a Figma node
2. A **revert toward verified Figma parity** — i.e., restoring code to
   match what Figma already says. Requires explicit user direction (e.g.
   "revert Phase 16/17 token bumps"). The revert must be sourced from a
   known-good commit (e.g. the most recent Figma sync) or a fresh
   Figma read, not a guess.
3. The **`release.sh` workflow** for snapshotting `uds/` into
   `versions/<X>/uds/` at release time. This doesn't *modify* the
   current `uds/` — it copies it.

Any other proposed write into `uds-docs/uds/` must stop and ask the user.

## Files outside `uds-docs/uds/`

Files outside `uds-docs/uds/` — i.e., `uds-docs/docs/**`,
`uds-docs/index.html`, `uds-docs/version.txt`, `uds-docs/scripts/**`,
`uds-docs/AGENTS.md`, `uds-docs/README.md`, `scripts/**` at the repo
root, `.cursor/**`, `AGENTS.md` at the repo root — are documentation-site
infrastructure or repo-level tooling. They are agent-modifiable under
the normal workflow (`uds-master-preflight.mdc`,
`uds-site-changelog.mdc`).

Note that site-side CSS like `uds-docs/docs/site.css` is also fair game
for the agent: the `.sg-*` classes that style the documentation chrome
are NOT the design system. Only the `.udc-*` classes inside
`uds-docs/uds/components/<id>/<id>.css` are.

## When an audit reports a failure under `uds-docs/uds/`

The correct agent response:

1. **Report** the finding: which audit, which page/component/token,
   which WCAG criterion or rule, what the measured value is, what the
   threshold is.
2. **Propose** options. For contrast failures, at minimum:
   - (a) accept the failure as a documented exception
   - (b) change a foreground token at the component or site-CSS layer
     (only allowed if the foreground swap doesn't itself touch
     `uds-docs/uds/` — i.e. it's a `.sg-*` site class or external
     consumer)
   - (c) introduce a new `*-bold` or otherwise-qualified surface variant
     in Figma, then re-sync
   - (d) bump the offending token in Figma, then re-sync
3. **Wait** for the user to pick a path. Do not apply any option that
   modifies `uds-docs/uds/`.

The audit script itself (`scripts/audit-theme-contrast.sh` and its
underlying `scripts/lib/audit_theme_contrast.js`) is read-only by design
and does not modify any file. Failing CI is the intended UX for surfacing
the design conversation. A red CI build is not a bug to silence by
editing tokens.

## Why this rule exists

The agent that ran Phase 16 and Phase 17 of the repo restructure
(commits `6022fcd` and `6564ae8`) saw axe-core report 308 contrast
violations and decided to fix them by bumping ~38 token values in
`uds/tokens/semantic.css` (including the AnyoneHome and Inhabit brand
accents — a visible brand-identity shift). It also swapped primitive
token references for semantic ones in `uds/components/button/button.css`.

None of those changes were sourced from Figma. None had user
authorization as a design change. They shipped under UDS 0.3 without a
version bump or a Figma round-trip, putting Figma and code in silent
disagreement for ~3 days until the user spotted the brand-color shift.
PR #7 (commit `fbb9a16`+) reverted all of that to the post-Figma-sync
0.3 state.

This rule codifies the lesson so a future agent doesn't reach the same
"helpful" conclusion when it sees a red CI run.

